#Text=Gniezno
#Text=Gniezno is a city in Greater Poland in Poland .
#Text=It is traditionally regarded as having been the first capital of Poland , and has been witness to many important events in early Polish history .
#Text=Gniezno has become the seat of the second Polish diocese ( after Poznań ) and the first archbishopric .
#Text=The coronations of several kings of Poland took place in the Gniezno cathedral .
#Text=Gniezno is situated in the northeastern part of the Greater Poland , between three lakes : Jelonek , Swietokrzyskie and Winiary , in what is called the Gniezno Lake District .
#Text=It is only 50 kilometres away from Poznań and relatively close to Kujawsko-Pomorskie .
#Text=By plane
#Text=The nearest airports with scheduled passenger service are in Poznań ( 50 km ) and Bydgoszcz ( 90 km ) .
#Text=By train
#Text=Gniezno is an important railroad junction , so there are many options to travel to and from the city by rail .
#Text=The main rail line through Gniezno is Poznań -Gniezno- Inowrocław , where it is forks out to Gdańsk through Bydgoszcz and to Olsztyn through Toruń , with numerous connections :
#Text=to Poznań
#Text=up to 17 daily regional trains and 6-10 ( depending on season ) fast ones .
#Text=The travel time to Poznań varies from 40-45 for fast trains to 55 for the local ones ( stopping at every station ) .
#Text=to Bydgoszcz and Gdańsk : 4 regional trains and 4-7 fast ones
#Text=to Toruń and Olsztyn
#Text=2 local trains and 3 fast ones .
#Text=Another line runs from Gniezno to Września and Jarocin , with 4 local trains daily ( including two coordinated in Jarocin with trains to Wrocław ) .
#Text=An interesting alternative for those traveling to Gniezno from the South-East is a journey by a local narrow-gauge railway .
#Text=It runs over a 38 km route during spring and summer weekends , and on other days by special request .
#Text=Details ( Polish only ) - .
#Text=By bus
#Text=Gniezno is a big bus travel junction , as well .
#Text=Most coaches go not - as you might think - to Poznań ( trains are dominating on this route ) , but to other places in the region ( only routes to tourist places are mentioned ) :
#Text=Bydgoszcz : 7 buses daily
#Text=Czerniejewo ( a beautiful historic palace ) :
#Text=more than 30 daily
#Text=Imiolki
#Text=( the Dominican Fish-Gate ) :
#Text=11 daily
#Text=Konin :
#Text=14 buses
#Text=daily
#Text=Kruszwica through Strzelno :
#Text=8 daily
#Text=Skorzecin ( a lake resort ) : 12
#Text=daily
#Text=Wenecja
#Text=through Biskupin : 9 buses daily
#Text=Wągrowiec : 9 daily
#Text=Września : 18 daily
#Text=Żnin : 10 buses daily
#Text=By car

#Text=The main road passing through Gniezno is the country road nr 5 , linking the town with Poznań and Wrocław in the south and with Bydgoszcz and Gdańsk in the north and passing through such attractions like Biskupin , Wenecja or Znin .

#Text=The other roads passing through Gniezno are : country road nr 15 - enablling you to get to Kruszwica , Strzelno or Toruń ; local road nr 260 - for those travelling in the Lake District nearby Powidz , 190 - to Wągrowiec and 197 to Slawa through the northern parts of Lednicki Landscape Park .
#Text=On foot
#Text=Most tourists will find it unnecessary to use public transport in Gniezno , as all main tourist attractions are situated in the very centre ( 6-8 minute walk from both rail and bus station ) .
#Text=By bus
#Text=The network consists of 16 city bus lines and 1 suburban line .
#Text=Some lines run only few times a day ( e.g. in peak hours ) .
#Text=The fee structure is simple - single ride will cost you 2 zloty ( 0.45€ ) , the fee doubles at night ( 23-5 ) .
#Text=If you travel more , you can use 11-ride ticket for 21 zloty .

#Text=Unfortunately , there 're no multiple-day tickets , the only option for those staying in the city for longer are monthly tickets - for one line : 50 zlotys ( 12€ ) , for two lines : 60 , for the whole network : 100 zlotys .
#Text=More information : free phone number : 9285 or .
#Text=Tourist information
#Text=The regional Tourist Information Centre , Rynek Sq . , Phone / fax : +48614284100 , mailto : turystyka@powiat-gniezno . pl
#Text=Polish Country-Lovers ’ Society , the Gniezno department , 10 , Łaskiego str. Phone : +48 61 425 37 37 , fax +48 61 426 36 60
#Text=See

#Text=The Assumption and St. Adalbert 's Cathedral , with the reliquaries of St. Adalbert ( Czech : Wojtiech ; Polish : Wojciech ) , famous Romanesque bronze door from c. 1170 , the most precious monument of romanesque art in Poland , the tombs of St. Adalbert and numerous Gothic , Renaissance and Baroque monuments and tombs of Gniezno bishops and archbishops and some Polish primates .

#Text=The Archbishopric Archives contain numerous documents including papal bulls from the early Middle Ages , the most precious of which are the Golden Gniezno Codex , the bulla od pope Innocent II from 1136 and the pergamine Gospel book - a manuscript from France from c. 800 .
#Text=The Gothic Church of St. John the Baptist from the mid 19th century , with unique polichromy in the presbytery .
#Text=More :

#Text=The Archbishopric Museum with precious liturgical vessels , including the chalice of St. Adalbert , chalice of Dobrava ( the wife of first polish Dukre , buried in Poznań ) or the Royal Chalice .
#Text=The Gothic Parish church of the Holy Trinity from the 15th century

#Text=The Gothic-Baroque Franciscan Assumption and St. Anthony 's Church with the miraculous icon of Our Lady , the Mistress of Gniezno ; next door is the Baroque Franciscan Monastery from the 18th century
#Text=Gothic Church of St. Michael Archangel from the 15th century , rebuilt in 1815 with a neo-Baroque rower from 1900 .
#Text=The Primates ' Palace
#Text=Visits to the Bronze Door and the cathedral 's crypt are permitted only with a guide .
#Text=Museums

#Text=The Gniezno Archbishopric Museum , 2 Kolegiaty str. , Phone : +48 61 426 37 78 , open 9.00-17.30 ( May-Sep , except Mondays ) or 9.00-15.00 ( Oct-Apr , except Sundays , Mondays and church holidays )
#Text=The Museum of Beginnings of The Polish State
#Text=1 , Kostrzewskiego str. , mailto : info@mppp . pl , Phone : +48 61 426 46 41 , open from Tuesday to Sunday 9:30 - 17:30 ( May – Sep ) or 10.00-17.00 ( Oct-Apr ) .
#Text=As the main part of the museum is an interactive show about the earliest polish history , one needs to make an obligatory advance booking !
#Text=The Municipal Museum - to be opened soon .
